\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf2 \cb3 In mid-October 2008, the American Studies Association (ASA) hosted its annual conference in Albuquerque, New Mexico.\cb4 \'a0According to its website, the ASA \'93is the nation\'92s oldest and largest association devoted to the interdisciplinary study of American culture and history.\'94\cb3 \'a0Over the past two decades, the ASA conference has emerged as a leading venue for vibrant discussions about\'a0race, ethnicity, transnationalism, gender, and sexuality.\cb4 \'a0While the ASA represents scholars with a diverse array of methodological approaches from a variety of disciplines, the society is a welcome home to academics whose work is interpretative and theoretical.\cb3 \'a0During the meeting, I attended a variety of panels engaging such issues and approaches and came away feeling energized and refreshed, my intellectual imagination stoked by the many ways in which race and ethnicity were wielded as central terms of analysis throughout the long weekend.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The following week, I was off to Baltimore where I attended \'93Tools for Data-Driven Scholarship,\'94 a workshop funded by the National Science Foundation (NSF), the National Endowment for the Humanities, and the Institute of Museum and Library Services.\cb4 \'a0This invitation-only event was cohosted by George Mason University\'92s Center for History and New Media (CHNM) and the Maryland Institute for Technology in the Humanities (MITH), two pioneering centers of what we have recently begun to call the \'93digital humanities.\'94\cb3 \'a0This workshop built upon several years\'92 conversation\'a0(particularly following the 2003 NSF Atkins Report on cyberinfrastructure)\'a0about the need for a digital infrastructure for humanities computing.\'a0\cb4 The\'a0\cb3 goal of the workshop\cb4 \'a0was defined in the e-mail invite as a report\'a0\cb3 \'93that\'a0discusses the\'a0needs of tools developers and users; sets forth\'a0objectives for addressing those needs; proposes\'a0infrastructure for accomplishing these objectives; and makes\'a0suggestions for a possible RFP.\'94\cb4 \'a0This meeting was also lively, full of thoughtful discussions about the possibilities for (and obstacles in the way of)\'a0\cb3 a robust infrastructure for scholars engaged in computation and the humanities.\'a0The conversation certainly fired up my technological imagination and subsequently led to useful discussions with my collaborators in technological design.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0901"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 \cb4 1}}\cb1 \
\cb3 As I flew home following this second event, I found myself reflecting on how far my thoughts had ranged in the course a mere week:\'a0from diaspora to database, from oppression to ontology, from visual studies to visualizations.\'a0And, once again,\'a0I found myself\'a0wondering\'a0why it seemed so hard to hold together\'a0my long-standing academic interests in race, gender, and certain modes of theoretical inquiry with my more recent (if decade-old) immersion in the world of digital production and design.\cb1 \
\cb3 While the workshop I participated in at ASA was titled \'93American Studies at the Digital Crossroads\'94 and drew a nice crowd, the conference as a whole included remarkably little discussion of digital technologies (although there were some analyses of digital texts such as websites and video games.){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0902"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 \cb4 2}}\cb4 \'a0It is largely accurate, if also a generalization, to say that\'a0\cb3 many in the membership of the ASA\'a0treat computation within the humanities with some level of\'a0suspicion, perceiving it to be complicit with the corporatization of higher education or as\'a0primarily technological rather than scholarly.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0903"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 3}}\cb4 \'a0(Indeed, this attitude is shared by a large number of \'93traditional\'94 humanities scholars across any number of fields or professional societies who do not work with digital media.)\'a0\cb3 In a hallway chat following our workshop, one scholar framed his dis-ease as a question: \'93Why are the digital humanities, well, so white?\'94\cb4 \'a0And while my\'a0\cb3 memory is far from perfect, I think it is\'a0safe to say\cb4 \'a0that\'a0\cb3 the Baltimore\'a0workshop included\'a0no discussion of many topics much in evidence at ASA, topics including immigration, race, and neoliberalism.\'a0To be fair,\'a0\cb4 this was a workshop focused on the notion of tools and infrastructure,\'a0\cb3 so one might not expect such discussions\cb4 . Nonetheless,\'a0\cb3 this essay will argue that\'a0we desperately need to close the gap\'a0between these two modes of inquiry.\cb4 \'a0Further, I will argue that\'a0\cb3 the\'a0difficulties we encounter in knitting together our discussions of race (or other modes of difference) with our technological productions within the digital humanities (or in our studies of code)\'a0are actually an\'a0
\f1\i effect
\f0\i0 \'a0of the very designs of our technological systems, designs that emerged in post\'96World War II computational culture.\'a0These origins of the digital continue to\'a0haunt\'a0our scholarly engagements with computers,\'a0underwriting the ease with which we partition off considerations of race in our work in the digital humanities and digital media studies.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\fs24 \cf2 \cb4 U.S. Operating Systems at Midcentury: The Intertwining of Race and UNIX\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf2 \cb4 Let us turn to two fragments cut from history, during the 1960s.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa96\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 FRAGMENT ONE\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 In the early 1960s, computer scientists at MIT were working on Project MAC, an early set of experiments in Compatible Timesharing Systems for computing. By 1965, MULTICS (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service), a mainframe timesharing operating system, was in use, with joint development by MIT, GE, and Bell Labs, a subsidiary of AT&T. The project was funded by ARPA (Advanced Research Projects Agency) of the Defense Department for two million dollars a year for eight years. MULTICS introduced early ideas about\'a0\cb3 modularity\cb4 \'a0in hardware structure and software architecture.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 In 1969, Bell Labs stopped working on MULTICS, and that summer one of their engineers, Ken Thompson, developed the beginning of UNIX. While there are clearly influences of MULTICS on UNIX, the later system also moves away from the earlier one, pushing for increased modularity and for a simpler design\'a0\cb3 able to run on cheaper computers\cb4 .\cb1 \
\cb4 In simplest terms,\'a0\cb3 UNIX is an early operating system for digital computers\cb4 , one that has spawned many offshoots and clones. These include MAC OS X as well as LINUX, indicating the reach of UNIX over the past forty years. The system also influenced non-UNIX operating systems like Windows NT and remains in use by many corporate IT divisions. UNIX was originally written in assembly language, but after Thompson\'92s colleague Dennis Ritchie developed the C programming language in 1972, Thompson rewrote UNIX in that language. Basic text-formatting and editing features were added (i.e., early word processors). In 1974, Ritchie and Thompson published their work in the journal of the\'a0
\f1\i Association for Computing Machinery,
\f0\i0 \'a0and UNIX began to pick up a good deal of steam.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0904"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 4}}\cb1 \
\cb4 U\cb3 NIX can also be thought of as more than an operating system, as it also includes a number of utilities such as command line editors, APIs, code libraries, and so on. Furthermore,\'a0UNIX is widely understood to embody particular\'a0philosophies and cultures of computation, \'93operating systems\'94 of a larger order that we will return to.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa96\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 FRAGMENT TWO\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 Of course, for scholars of culture, of gender, and of race like the members of the ASA, dates like 1965 and 1968 have other resonances. For many of us,\'a0\cb3 1965 might not recall MULTICS but instead the\'a0assassination of Malcolm X\cb4 , the f\cb3 ounding of the\'a0United Farm Workers,\'a0the\'a0burning of Watts, or the\'a0passage of the Voting Rights Act\cb4 . The mid-1960s also saw the origins of the\'a0\cb3 American Indian Movement (AIM) and the launch of the National Organization for Women (NOW)\cb4 . The late 1960s mark the 1968 citywide walkouts of Latino youth in Los Angeles, the\'a0\cb3 assassinations of Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert F. Kennedy, the Chicago Democratic Convention, the Stonewall Riots, and the founding of the Black Panthers and the Young Lords\cb4 . Beyond the geographies of the United States, we might also remember the\'a0\cb3 Prague Spring of 1968, Tommie Smith and John Carlos at the Mexico Summer Olympics, the Tlatelolco Massacre, the execution of Che Guevara, the Chinese Cultural Revolution, the Six-Day War, or May \'9268 in Paris\cb4 . On the African continent,\'a0\cb3 thirty-two countries gained independence from colonial rulers\cb4 .\'a0\cb3 In the United States, broad cultural shifts emerged across the decade, as identity politics took root and countercultural forces challenged traditional values.\cb4 \'a0Resistance to the Vietnam War mounted as the decade wore on.\'a0\cb3 Abroad, movements against colonialism and oppression were notably strong.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The history just glossed as \'93Fragment One\'94 is well known to code junkies and computer geeks.\'a0Numerous websites archive oral histories, programming manuals, and technical specifications for MULTICS, UNIX, and various mainframe and other hardware systems.\cb4 \'a0\cb3 Key players in that history, including Ken Thompson, Donald Ritchie, and Doug McIlroy, have a kind of geek-chic celebrity status\cb4 , and differing versions of the histories of software and hardware development are hotly debated, including nitty-gritty details of what really counts as \'93a UNIX.\'94\cb3 \'a0In media studies, emerging work in \'93code studies\'94 often resurrects and takes up these histories.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0905"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 \cb4 5}}\cb1 \
\cb3 Within American, cultural, and ethnic studies, the temporal touchstones of struggles over racial justice, antiwar activism, and legal history are also widely recognized and analyzed\cb4 .\cb3 \'a0Not surprisingly,\'a0these two fragments typically stand apart in parallel tracks, attracting the interest and attention of very different audiences located in the deeply\'a0siloed\'a0departments that categorize our universities.\cb1 \

\f1\i \cb3 But why?
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\cb3 In short,\'a0I suggest that\'a0these\'a0two moments are deeply interdependent.\'a0In fact,\'a0they coconstitute one another, comprising not independent slices of history but instead related and useful lenses into the shifting epistemological registers driving U.S. and global culture in the 1960s and after.\cb1 \
\cb3 This history of intertwining and mutual dependence is hard to sketch.\'a0As one delves into the intricacies of UNIX (or of XML), race in America recedes far from our line of vision and inquiry.\'a0Likewise, detailed examinations into the shifting registers of race and racial visibility post-1950 do not easily lend themselves to observations about the emergence of object-oriented programming or the affordances of databases.\'a0Very few audiences who care about one lens have much patience or tolerance for the other.\cb1 \
\cb4 Early forays into new media theory in the late 1990s and much concurrent work in the computational humanities rarely helped this problem.\cb3 \'a0Theorists of new media often retreated into forms of analysis that\'a0Marsha Kinder has critiqued as \'93cyberstructuralist,\'94\'a0intent on parsing media specificity and on\'a0theorizing the forms of new media while disavowing twenty-plus years of critical race theory, feminism, and other modes of\'a0overtly politicized inquiry.\'a0Much of the work in the\'a0digital humanities also proceeded\'a0as if technologies from XML to databases were neutral tools.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0906"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 \cb4 6}}\cb4 \'a0\cb3 Many who had worked hard to instill race as a central mode of analysis in film, literary, and media studies throughout the late twentieth century were disheartened and outraged (if not that surprised) to find\'a0both new media theory and emerging digital tools seem\'a0indifferent\'a0to those hard-won gains.\cb1 \
\cb3 Early analyses of race and the digital often took two forms:\'a0first,\'a0a critique of representations\'a0
\f1\i in
\f0\i0 \'a0new media\'a0or the\'a0building of digital archives\'a0about race, modes that largely were deployed at the surface of our screens, or,\'a0second,\'a0debates about access to media\'97that is, the digital divide.\cb4 \'a0S\cb3 uch work\'a0rarely tied race to the analyses of form, phenomenology, or computation\'a0that were so compelling in the work of Lev Manovich, Mark Hansen, or Jay Bolter and Richard Grusin.\'a0Important works emerged from both \'93camps,\'94 but the camps rarely intersected.\'a0\cb4 A few events attempted to force a collision between these areas, but the going was tough. For instance, at the two Race and Digital Space Conferences colleagues and I organized in 2000 and 2002, the vast majority of participants and speakers were engaged in work in the two modes mentioned earlier. The\'a0\cb3 cyberstructuralists were not in attendance.\cb1 \
\cb4 But what if this very incompatability is itself part and parcel of the organization of knowledge production that operating systems like UNIX helped to disseminate around the world?\'a0\cb3 Might we ask whether there is not something\'a0
\f1\i particular to the very forms
\f0\i0 \'a0of electronic culture that seems to encourage just such a movement, a movement that\'a0partitions race off\'a0from the specificity of media forms?\'a0Put differently,\'a0might we argue that the very\'a0structures\'a0of digital computation develop at least in part to cordon off race and to contain it?\'a0Further, might we come to understand that our own critical methodologies are the heirs to this epistemological shift?\cb1 \
\cb3 From early writings by Sherry Turkle and George Landow to more recent work by Alex Galloway and others,\'a0new media scholars have noted the\'a0parallels between the ways of knowing modeled in computer culture and the greatest hits of structuralism and poststructuralism.\'a0Critical race theorists and postcolonial scholars like\'a0Chela Sandoval and Gayatri Spivak\'a0have illustrated the structuring (if unacknowledged) role that race plays in the work of poststructuralists like Roland Barthes and Michel Foucault\cb4 .\cb3 \'a0We might bring these two arguments together,\'a0triangulating race, electronic culture, and poststructuralism, and, further, argue that race, particularly in the United States, is central to this undertaking, fundamentally shaping how we see and know as well as the technologies that underwrite or cement both vision and knowledge.\'a0Certain modes of racial visibility and knowing coincide or dovetail with specific ways of organizing data: if digital computing underwrites today\'92s information economy and is the central technology of post\'96World War II America,\'a0these technologized ways of seeing and knowing took shape in a world also struggling with shifting knowledges about and representations of race.\'a0If, as Michael Omi and Howard Winant argue, racial formations serve as fundamental organizing principles of social relations in the United States, on both the macro and micro levels (55), how might we understand the infusion of racial organizing principles into the technological organization of knowledge after World War II?\cb1 \
\cb3 Omi and Winant and other\'a0scholars have tracked\'a0the emergence of a \'93race-blind\'94 rhetoric at midcentury,\'a0a discourse that moves from overt to more covert modes of racism and racial representation (e.g., from the era of Jim Crow to liberal colorblindness).\'a0Drawing from those 3-D postcards that bring two or more images together even while suppressing their connections, I have earlier termed the racial paradigms of the postwar era \'93lenticular logics.\'94\'a0The ridged coating on 3-D postcards is actually a lenticular lens, a structural device that makes simultaneously viewing the various images contained on one card nearly impossible.\'a0The viewer can rotate the card to see any single image, but the lens itself makes seeing the images\'a0
\f1\i together
\f0\i0 \'a0very difficult, even as it conjoins them at a structural level (i.e., within the same card).\'a0In the post\'96civil rights United States, the lenticular is a way of organizing the world.\'a0It structures representations but also epistemologies. It also serves to secure our understandings of race in very narrow registers,\'a0fixating on sameness or difference while forestalling connection and interrelation.\'a0As I have argued elsewhere, we might think of the lenticular as a covert mode of the pretense of separate but equal,\'a0remixed for midcentury America (McPherson, 250).\cb1 \
\cb3 A lenticular logic is a covert racial logic, a logic for the post\'96civil rights era.\'a0We might contrast the lenticular postcard to that wildly popular artifact of the industrial era, the stereoscope card.\'a0The\'a0stereoscope melds two different images into an imagined whole, privileging the whole; the lenticular image partitions and divides, privileging fragmentation.\'a0A\'a0lenticular logic is a logic of the fragment or the chunk, a way of seeing the world as discrete modules or nodes, a mode that suppresses relation and context.\'a0As such, the lenticular also manages and controls complexity.\cb1 \
\cb4 And what in the world does this have to do with those engineers laboring away at Bell Labs, the heroes of the first fragment of history this essay began with? What\'92s race got to do with that?\'a0\cb3 The popularity of lenticular lenses, particularly in the form of postcards, coincides historically not just with the rise of an articulated movement for civil rights but also with the growth of electronic culture and the birth of digital computing\cb4 \'a0(with both\'97digital computing and the civil rights movement\'97born in quite real ways of World War II).\cb3 \'a0We might understand UNIX as the way in which the emerging logics of the lenticular and of the covert racism of color blindness get ported into our computational systems, both in terms of the specific functions of UNIX as an operating system and in the broader philosophy it embraces.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa96\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 SITUATING UNIX\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 In moving toward UNIX from MULTICS, programmers conceptualized UNIX as a kind of tool kit of \'93synergistic parts\'94 that allowed \'93flexibility in depth\'94 (Raymond, 9). Programmers could \'93choose among multiple shells\'85. [and] programs normally provide[d] many behavior options\'94 (6).\cb3 \'a0One of the design philosophies driving UNIX is the notion that a program should\'a0do one thing and do it well (not unlike our deep disciplinary drive in many parts of the university); this privileging of the discrete, the local, and the specific emerges again and again in discussions of UNIX\'92s origins and design\'a0philosophies.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 Books for programmers that explain the\'a0\cb3 UNIX philosophy revolve around a common set of rules.\'a0\cb4 While slight variations on this rule set exist across programming books and online sites, Eric Raymond sets out the first nine rules as follows:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li288\sl320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Rule of Modularity: Write simple parts connected by\'a0clean\'a0interfaces.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li288\sl320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 Rule of Clarity: Clarity is better than cleverness.\cb1 \
\cb4 Rule of Composition: Design programs to be connected to other programs.\cb1 \
\cb4 Rule of Separation:\'a0\cb3 Separate\cb4 \'a0policy from mechanism; separate interfaces from engines.\cb1 \
\cb4 Rule of Simplicity: Design for simplicity; add complexity only where you must.\cb1 \
\cb4 Rule of Parsimony: Write a big program only when it is clear by demonstration that nothing else will do.\cb1 \
\cb4 Rule of Transparency: Design for visibility to make inspection and debugging easier.\cb1 \
\cb4 Rule of Robustness: Robustness is the child of transparency and simplicity.\cb1 \
\cb4 Rule of Representation: Fold knowledge into data so program logic can be stupid and robust. (13)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 Other rules include the Rules of Least Surprise, Silence, Repair, Economy, Generation, Optimization, Diversity, and Extensibility.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0907"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 7}}\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 These rules implicitly translate into computational terms the chunked logics of the lenticular.\'a0\cb4 For instance, Brian Kernighan wrote in a 1976 handbook on software programming that\'a0\cb3 \'93controlling complexity is the essence of computer programming\'94\cb4 \'a0(quoted in Raymond, 14). Complexity in UNIX is controlled in part by the Rule of Modularity, which insists that code be constructed of discrete and interchangeable parts that can be plugged together via clean interfaces. In\'a0
\f1\i Design Rules, Vol. 1: The Power of Modularity
\f0\i0 , Carliss Baldwin and Kim Clark argue that computers from 1940 to 1960 had \'93complex, interdependent designs,\'94 and they label this era the \'93premodular\'94 phase of computing (149). While individuals within the industry, including John von Neumann, were beginning to imagine benefits to modularity in computing, Baldwin and Clark note that von Neumann\'92s ground-breaking designs for computers in that period \'93fell short of true modularity\'94 because \'93in no sense was the detailed design of one component going to be hidden from the others: all pieces of the system would be produced \'91in full view\'92 of the others\'94 (157). Thus one might say that these early visions of digital computers were neither modular nor lenticular. Baldwin and Clark track the increasing modularity of hardware design from the early 1950s forward and also observe that UNIX was the first operating system to embrace modularity and adhere \'93to the principles of information hiding\'94 in its design (324).\cb1 \
\cb3 There are clearly practical advantages of such structures for coding, but they also underscore a worldview in which a troublesome part might be discarded without disrupting the whole.\cb4 \'a0\cb3 Tools are meant to be \'93encapsulated\'94 to avoid \'93a tendency to involve programs with each others\'92 internals\'94 (Raymond, 15).\'a0Modules \'93don\'92t promiscuously share global data,\'94 and problems can stay \'93local\'94 (84\'9685).\cb4 \'a0In writing about the Rule of Composition, Eric Raymond advises programmers to \'93make [programs] independent.\'94 He writes, \'93It should be easy to replace one end with a completely different implementation without disturbing the other\'94 (15).\'a0\cb3 Detachment is valued because it allows a cleaving from \'93the particular \'85conditions under which a design problem was posed.\cb4 \'a0Abstract. Simplify. Generalize\'94 (95).\cb3 \'a0While \'93generalization\'94 in UNIX\'a0has specific meanings, we might also see at work here\'a0the basic contours of\'a0a lenticular approach to the world, an approach that separates object from context, cause from effect.\cb1 \
\cb4 In a 1976 article, \'93Software Tools,\'94 Bell Lab programmers Kernighan and P. J. Plauger urged programmers \'93to view specific jobs as special cases of general, frequently performed operations, so they can make and use general-purpose tools to solve them.\cb3 \'a0We also hope to show how to design programs to look like tools and to interconnect conveniently\'94 (1).\cb4 \'a0While the language here is one of generality (as in \'93general purpose\'94 tools), in fact, the tool library that is being envisioned is a series of very discrete and specific tools or programs that can operate independently of one another. T\cb3 hey continue, \'93Ideally, a program should not know where its input comes from nor where its output goes.\cb4 \'a0The UNIX time-sharing system provides a particularly elegant way to handle input and output redirection\'94 (2). Programs can profitably be described as filters, even though they do quite complicated transformations on their input. One should be able to say\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li288\sl320\sa192\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 program-1 \'85 | sort | program-2 \'85\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 and have the output of program-1 sorted before being passed to program-2. This has the major advantage that neither program-1 nor program-2 need know how to sort, but can concentrate on its main task (4).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 In effect, the tools chunk computational programs into isolated bits where the programs\'92 operations are meant to be \'93invisible to the user\'94 and to the other programs in a sequence: \'93the point is that this operation is invisible to the user (or should be)\'85.\cb4 \'a0Instead he sees simply a program with one input and one output.\cb3 \'a0Unsorted data go in one end; somewhat later, sorted data come out the other.\cb4 \'a0\cb3 It must be\'a0
\f1\i convenient
\f0\i0 \'a0to use a tool, not just possible\'94\cb4 \'a0(5). Kernighan and Plauger saw the \'93filter concept\'94 as a useful way to get programmers to think in discrete bits and to simplify their code, reducing the potential complexity of programs. They note that \'93when a job is viewed as a series of filters, the implementation simplifies, for it is broken down into a sequence of relatively independent pieces, each small and easily tested. This is a form of high-level modularization\'94 (5).\'a0\cb3 In their own way, these filters function as a kind of lenticular frame or lens, allowing only certain portions of complex data sets to be visible at a particular time to both the user and the machine.\cb1 \
\cb4 The technical feature that allowed UNIX to achieve much of its modularity was the development by Ken Thompson (based on a suggestion by Doug McIlroy) of the pipe\'97that is,\'a0\cb3 a vertical bar that replaced the symbol for greater than (>) in the operating system\'92s code.\cb4 \'a0As described by Doug Ritchie and Ken Thompson in a paper for the Association of Computing Machinery in 1974 (reprinted by Bell Labs in 1978), \'93A\'a0
\f1\i read
\f0\i0 \'a0using a pipe file descriptor waits until another process writes using the file descriptor for the same pipe. At this point, data are passed between the images of the two processes. Neither process need know that a pipe, rather than an ordinary file, is involved\'94 (480). In this way, the ability to construct a pipeline from a series of small programs evolved, while the \'93hiding of internals\'94 was also supported. The contents of a module were not central to the functioning of the pipeline; rather, the input or output (a text stream) was key.\'a0Brian Kernighan noted \'93that while input/output direction predates pipes,\'a0\cb3 the development of pipes led to the concept of tools\cb4 \'97software programs that would be in a \'91tool box,\'92 available when you need them\'94 and interchangeable.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0908"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 8}}\'a0P\cb3 ipes\'a0reduced complexity\'a0and were also linear\cb4 . In \'93Software Tools,\'94 Kernighan and Plauger extend their discussion of pipes, noting that \'93a pipe provides a\'a0\cb3 hidden buffering between the output of one program and the input of another program\cb4 \'a0so information may pass between them without ever entering the file system\'94 (2).\'a0They also signal the importance of pipes for issues of data security:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li288\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 And consider the sequence\cb1 \
\cb4 decrypt key <file | prog | encrypt key > newfile\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li288\sl320\sa192\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 Here a decryption program decodes an encrypted file, passing the decoded characters to a program having no special security features. The ouput of the program is re-encrypted at the other end. If a true pipe mechanism is used, no clear-text version of the data will ever appear in a file. To simulate this sequence with temporary files risks breaching security. (3)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 While the affordances of filters, pipes, and hidden data are often talked about as a matter of simple standardization and efficiency (as when Kernighan and Plauger argue that \'93our emphasis here has been on getting jobs done with an efficient use of people\'94 [6]), they also clearly work in the service of\'a0new regimes of security,\'a0not an insignificant detail in the context of the cold war era.\'a0Programming manuals and UNIX guides again and again stress\'a0clarity and simplicity\'a0(don\'92t write fancy code; say what you mean as clearly and directly as you can), but\'a0the structures of operating systems like UNIX function by hiding internal operations, skewing \'93clarity\'94 in very particular directions.\'a0\cb4 These manuals privilege a programmer\'92s equivalent of common sense in the Gramscian sense.\cb3 \'a0For Antonio Gramsci, common sense is a historically situated process, the way in which a particular group responds to \'93certain problems posed by reality which are quite specific\'94 at a particular time (324).\'a0As programmers constituted themselves as a particular class of workers in the 1970s, they were necessarily lodged in their moment,\'a0deploying common sense\'a0and notions about simplicity to justify their innovations in code.\'a0Importantly, and as we will see, this moment is overdetermined by the ways in which\'a0the United States is widely coming to process race and other forms of difference in more covert registers, as noted earlier, even if the programmers themselves do not explicitly understand their work to be tied to such racial paradigms.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0909"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 \cb4 9}}\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 Another rule of UNIX is the\'a0\cb3 Rule of Diversity, which insists on a mistrust of the \'93one true way.\'94\cb4 \'a0\cb3 Thus UNIX, in the words of one account, \'93embraces multiple languages, open extensible systems and customization hooks everywhere,\'94 reading much like a description of the tenets of neoliberal multiculturalism\cb4 \'a0(Raymond, 24). Certain words emerge again and again throughout the ample literature on UNIX: modularity, compactness, simplicity, orthogonality. UNIX is meant to allow multitasking, portability, time sharing, and compartmentalizing. It is not much of a stretch to layer these traits over the core tenets of post-Fordism, a mode of production that begins to remake industrial-era notions of standardization in the 1960s: time-space compression, transformability, customization, a public/private blur, and so on. UNIX\'92s intense modularity and information-hiding capacity were reinforced by its design\'97that is, in the ways in which it segregated the kernel from the shell. T\cb3 he kernel loads into the computer\'92s memory at start-up and is \'93the heart\'94 of UNIX (managing \'93hardware memory, job execution, and time sharing\'94), although it remains hidden from the user\'a0(Baldwin and Clark, 332).\cb4 \'a0The shells (or programs that interpret commands) are intermediaries between the user and the computer\'92s inner workings. They hide the details of the operating system from the user behind \'93the shell,\'94 extending modularity from a rule for programming in UNIX to the very design of UNIX itself.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0910"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 10}}\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\fs24 \cf2 \cb4 Modularity in the Social Field\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf2 \cb3 This\'a0push toward modularity and the covert in digital computation\'a0also reflects other changes in the organization of social life in the United States by the 1960s.\'a0For instance, if the first half of the twentieth century laid bare its racial logics, from \'93Whites Only\'94 signage to the brutalities of lynching, the second half increasingly hides its racial \'93kernel,\'94 burying it below a shell of neoliberal pluralism.\'a0These covert racial logics take hold at the tail end of the civil rights movement at least partially to cut off and contain the more radical logics implicit in the urban uprisings that shook Detroit, Watts, Chicago, and Newark.\'a0In fact,\'a0the urban center of Detroit was more segregated by the 1980s than in previous decades, reflecting a different inflection of the programmer\'92s vision of the \'93easy removal\'94 or containment of a troubling part.\'a0Whole areas of the city might be rendered orthogonal and disposable (also think post-Katrina New Orleans), and the urban black poor were increasingly isolated in \'93deteriorating city centers\'94 (Sugrue, 198).\'a0Historian Thomas Sugrue traces the increasing unemployment rates for black men in Detroit,\'a0rates that rose dramatically from the 1950s to the 1980s, and maps a \'93deproletarianization\'94 that \'93shaped a pattern of poverty in the postwar city that was surprisingly new\'94\'a0(262).\cb4 \'a0\cb3 Across several registers, the emerging neoliberal state begins to adopt the\'a0Rule of Modularity.\cb4 \'a0For instance, we might draw an example from across the Atlantic. In her careful analysis of the effects of May 1968 and its afterlives, Kristin Ross argues that the French government contained the radical force of the uprisings by quickly moving to separate the students\'92 rebellion from the concerns of labor, deploying a strategy of separation and containment in which both sides (students and labor) would ultimately lose (69).\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Modularity in software design was meant to decrease \'93global complexity\'94 and cleanly separate one \'93neighbor\'94 from another\'a0(Raymond, 85).\'a0These strategies also played out in ongoing reorganizations of the political field throughout the 1960s and 1970s\'a0in both the Right and the Left.\'a0\cb4 The widespread divestiture in the infrastructure of inner cities can be seen as one more insidious effect of the logic of modularity in the postwar era.\'a0\cb3 But we might also understand the emergence of identity politics in the 1960s as a kind of social and political embrace of modularity and encapsulation,\'a0a mode of partitioning that turned away from the broader forms of alliance-based and globally inflected political practice that characterized both labor politics and antiracist organizing in the 1930s and 1940s.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0911"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 \cb4 11}}\cb4 \'a0\cb3 While identity politics produced concrete gains in the world, particularly in terms of civil rights, we are also now coming to understand the degree to which these movements curtailed and short-circuited more radical forms of political praxis, reducing struggle to fairly discrete parameters.\cb1 \
\cb3 Let me be clear.\'a0By drawing\'a0analogies between shifting racial and political formations and the emerging structures of digital computing in the late 1960s, I am not arguing that the programmers creating UNIX at Bell Labs and in Berkeley were\'a0
\f1\i consciously
\f0\i0 \'a0encoding new modes of racism and racial understanding into digital systems.\cb4 \'a0(Indeed, many of these programmers were themselves left-leaning hippies, and the overlaps between the counterculture and early computing culture run deep, as Fred Turner has illustrated.)\'a0\cb3 I also recognize that their innovations made possible the word processor I am using to write this article,\cb4 \'a0a powerful tool that shapes cognition and scholarship in precise ways. Nor am I arguing for some exact correspondence between the ways in which encapsulation or modularity work in computation and how they function in the emerging regimes of neoliberalism, governmentality, and post-Fordism.\'a0\cb3 Rather,\'a0I am\'a0highlighting the ways in which\'a0the organization of information and capital in the 1960s powerfully responds\'97across many registers\'97to the struggles for racial justice and democracy that so categorized the United States at the time.\'a0Many of these shifts were enacted in the name of liberalism, aimed at distancing the overt racism of the past even as they contained and cordoned off progressive radicalism.\'a0The emergence of covert racism and its rhetoric of color blindness are not so much intentional as systemic.\'a0Computation is a primary delivery method of these new systems, and\'a0it seems at best\'a0naive to imagine that cultural and computational operating systems don\'92t mutually infect one another.\cb1 \
\cb3 Thus we see modularity take hold not only in computation but also in the increasingly\'a0niched and regimented production of knowledge in the university\'a0after World War II.\'a0For instance, Christopher Newfield comments on the rise of New Criticism in literature departments in the cold war era, noting its relentless formalism, a \'93logical corollary\'94 to \'93depoliticization\'94 (145) that \'93replaced agency with technique\'94 (155).\cb4 \'a0\cb3 He attributes this particular tendency in literary criticism at least in part to the triumph of a managerial impulse, a turn that we might also align (even if Newfield doesn\'92t) with the workings of modular code (itself studied as an exemplary approach to dynamic modeling systems for business management in the work of Baldwin and Clark cited earlier.){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0912"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 12}}\'a0\cb4 He observes as well that this managerial obsession within literary criticism exhibits a surprising continuity across the 1960s and beyond.\'a0\cb3 Gerald Graff\'a0has also examined the \'93patterned isolation\'94 that emerges in the university after World War II, at the moment when New Criticism\'92s methods take hold in a manner that deprivileges context and focuses on \'93explication for explication\'92s sake.\'94\cb4 \'a0Graff then analyzes the routinization of literary criticism in the period, a mechanistic exercise with input and output streams of its own (227).\'a0\cb3 He recognizes that university departments (his example is English) begin to operate by\'a0a field-based and modular strategy of \'93coverage,\'94 in which subfields proliferate and exist in their own separate chunks of knowledge, rarely contaminated by one another\'92s\'a0\'93internals\'94\'a0(250). (He also comments that this modular strategy includes the token hiring of scholars of color who are then cordoned off within the department.)\'a0\cb4 Graff locates the beginning of this\cb3 \'a0patterned isolation\cb4 \'a0in the run-up to the period that also brought us digital computing; he writes that it continues to play out today in disciplinary structures that have become increasingly narrow and specialized.\'a0\cb3 Patterned isolation begins with the bureaucratic standardization of the university from 1890 through 1930 (61\'9662), but this \'93cut out and separate\'94 mentality reaches a new crescendo after World War II as the organizational structure of the university pushes from simply bureaucratic and Taylorist to managerial\cb4 , a shift noted as well by Christopher Newfield.\'a0\cb3 Many now lament the\'a0overspecialization\'a0of the university; in effect, this tendency is a result of the additive logic of the lenticular or of the pipeline, where \'93content areas\'94 or \'93fields\'94 are tacked together without any sense of intersection, context, or relation.\'a0Today, we risk\'a0adding\'a0the digital humanities to our proliferating disciplinary menus without any meaningful and substantial engagement with fields such as gender studies or critical race theory.\cb1 \
\cb3 It is interesting to note that much of the early work performed in UNIX environments was focused on document processing and communication tools and that UNIX is a computational system that very much privileges text (it centers on the text-based command line instead of on the graphical user interface, and its inputs and outputs are simple text lines).\'a0Many of the methodologies of the humanities from the cold war through the 1980s also privilege text while devaluing\'a0context\'a0and operate in their own chunked systems, suggesting telling parallels between the operating systems and privileged objects of the humanities and of the computers being developed on several university campuses in the same period.\cb1 \
\cb3 Lev Manovich has, of course, noted the modularity of the digital era and also backtracked to early twentieth-century examples of modularity from the factory line to the creative productions of avant garde artists.\'a0In a posting to the Nettime listserv in 2005, he frames modularity as a uniquely twentieth-century phenomenon, from Henry Ford\'92s assembly lines to the 1932 furniture designs of Belgian designer Louis Herman De Kornick.\'a0In his account, the twentieth century is characterized by an accelerating process of industrial modularization,\'a0but\'a0I think it is useful to examine the digital computer\'92s privileged role in the process, particularly given that competing modes of computation were still quite viable until the 1960s, modes that might have pushed more toward the continuous flows of analog computing rather than the discrete tics of the digital computer.\'a0Is the modularity of the 1920s really the same as the modularity modeled in UNIX?\cb4 \'a0Do these differences matter, and what might we miss if we assume a smooth and teleological triumph of modularity?\cb3 \'a0How has computation pushed modularity in new directions, directions in dialogue with other cultural shifts and ruptures?\'a0Why does modularity emerge in our systems with such a vengeance\'a0across the 1960s?\cb1 \
\cb3 I have here suggested that\'a0our technological formations are deeply bound up with our racial formations and that each undergo profound changes at midcentury.\'a0I am not so much arguing that one mode is causally related to the other but, rather, that they both represent a move toward modular knowledges, knowledges increasingly prevalent in the second half of the twentieth century.\'a0These knowledges support and enable the shift from the overt standardized bureaucracies of the 1920s and 1930s to the more dynamically modular and\'a0covert\'a0managerial systems\'a0that are increasingly prevalent as the century wears on.\'a0These latter modes of knowledge production and organization are powerful racial and technological operating systems that coincide with (and reinforce) (post)structuralist approaches to the world within the academy.\'a0Both the computer and the lenticular lens mediate images and objects, changing their relationship but frequently suppressing that process of relation, much like the divided departments of the contemporary university.\'a0The fragmentary knowledges encouraged by many forms and experiences of the digital neatly parallel the logics that underwrite the covert racism endemic to our times,\'a0operating in potential feedback loops, supporting each other.\'a0If scholars of race have highlighted how certain tendencies within poststructuralist theory simultaneously respond to and marginalize race,\'a0this maneuver is at least partially possible because of a parallel and increasing dispersion of electronic forms across culture, forms that simultaneously enact and shape these new modes of thinking.\cb1 \
\cb3 While the examples here have focused on UNIX, it is important to recognize that the core principles of modularity that it helped bring into practice continue to impact a wide range of digital computation, especially the C programming language, itself developed for UNIX by Ritchie, based on Thompson\'92s earlier B language.\cb4 \'a0While UNIX and C devotees will bemoan the nonorthogonality and leakiness of Windows or rant about the complexity of C++, the basic argument offered earlier\'97that UNIX helped inaugurate modular and lenticular systems broadly across computation and culture\'97holds true for the black boxes of contemporary coding and numerous other instances of our digital praxis.\cb1 \
\cb3 Today, we might see contemporary turns in computing\'97neural nets, clouds, semantics, and so on\'97as parallel to\'a0recent turns in humanities scholarship to privilege networks over nodes (particularly in new media studies and in digital culture theory)\'a0and to focus on globalization and its flows (in American studies and other disciplines).\'a0While this may simply mean we have learned our midcentury lessons and are smarter now,\'a0we might also continue to examine with rigor and detail the degree to which dominant forms of computation\'97what David Golumbia has aptly called \'93the cultural logic of computation\'94 in his recent update of Frankfurt School pessimism for the twenty-first century\'97continue to respond to shifting racial and cultural formations.\cb4 \'a0\cb3 Might these emerging modes of computation be read as symptoms and drivers of our postracial moment, refracting in some way national anxieties (or hopes) about a decreasingly white America?\'a0We should also remain alert to how contemporary technoracial formations infect privileged ways of knowing in the academy\cb4 .\'a0\cb3 While both the tales of C. P. Snow circa 1959 and the Sokal science wars of the 1990s sustain the myth that science and the humanities operate in distinct realms of knowing, powerful operating systems have surged beneath the surface of what and how we know in the academy for well over half a decade.\'a0It would be foolish of us to believe that these operating systems\'97in this paper best categorized by UNIX and its many close siblings\'97do not at least partially overdetermine the very critiques we imagine that we are performing today.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\fs24 \cf2 \cb4 Moving Beyond Our Boxes\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf2 \cb3 So if we are\'a0always already complicit with the machine, what are we to do?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi192\sl320\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 First,\'a0we must better understand the machines and networks that continue to powerfully shape our lives in ways that we are often ill equipped to deal with as media and humanities scholars.\'a0This necessarily involves more than simply studying our screens and the images that dance across them,\'a0moving beyond the study of representations and the rhetorics of visuality.\'a0We might read representations seeking symptoms of information capital\'92s fault lines and successes, but we cannot read the logics of these systems and networks solely at the level of our screens.\'a0Capital is now fully organized under the sign of modularity.\'a0It operates via the algorithm and the database, via simulation and processing.\'a0Our screens are cover stories, disguising deeply divided forms of both machine and human labor.\'a0We focus exclusively on them increasingly to our peril.\cb1 \
\cb3 Scholars in the digital humanities and in the emerging field of code studies are taking up the challenge of understanding how computational systems (especially but not only software) developed and operate.\cb4 \'a0However, we must\'a0\cb3 demand that these fields not replay the formalist and structuralist tendencies of new media theory circa 1998.\cb4 \'a0This formalist turn displayed a stubborn technological determinism and often privileged the machine over the social. To end run such determinism,\cb3 \'a0the\'a0digital humanities and code studies must also take up the\'a0questions of culture and meaning\'a0that animate so many scholars of race in fields like the\'a0
\f1\i new
\f0\i0 \'a0American studies.\'a0Likewise,\'a0scholars of race must analyze, use, and produce digital forms and not smugly assume that to engage the digital directly is to be complicit with the forces of capitalism.\'a0The lack of intellectual generosity across our fields and departments only reinforces the divide-and-conquer mentality that the most dangerous aspects of modularity underwrite.\'a0We must develop common languages that link the study of code and culture. We must historicize and politicize code studies. And,\'a0because digital media were born as much of the civil rights era as of the cold war era\'a0(and of course these eras are one and the same),\'a0our investigations must incorporate race from the outset, understanding and theorizing its function as a ghost in the digital machine. This\'a0does not mean that we should simply add race to our analysis in a modular way, neatly tacking it on or building digital archives of racial material, but that\'a0we must understand and theorize the deep imbrications of race and digital technology even when our objects of analysis (say UNIX or search engines) seem not to be about race at all.\'a0\cb4 This will not be easy. In the writing of this essay, the logic of modularity continually threatened to take hold, leading me into detailed explorations of pipe structures in UNIX or departmental structures in the university, taking me far from the contours of race at midcentury. It is hard work to hold race and computation together in a systemic manner, but it is work that we must continue to undertake.\cb1 \
\cb3 We also need to take seriously the possibility that\'a0questions of representation and of narrative and textual analysis may, in effect, divert us from studying the reorganization of capital\'97a reorganization dependent on the triumph of the very particular patterns of informationalization evident in code.\'a0If the study of representation may in fact be part and parcel of the very logic of modularity that such code inaugurates, a kind of distraction, it\'a0is equally plausible to argue that our very intense focus on visuality in the past twenty years of scholarship is just a different manifestation of the same distraction.\'a0There is tendency in film and media studies to treat the computer and its screens as (in Jonathan Beller\'92s terms) a \'93legacy\'94 technology to cinema.\cb4 \'a0In its drive to stage continuities, such an argument tends to minimize or completely miss the fundamental material differences between cinematic visuality and the production of the visual by digital technologies.\cb3 \'a0For most of the twentieth century, cinema was a profoundly visual (if also aural) form, with images etched into celluloid; the digital does not depend on vision in any analogous way.\cb1 \
\cb3 To push my\'a0polemic\'a0to its furthest dimensions, I would argue that\'a0to study image, narrative, and visuality will never be enough if we do not engage as well the nonvisual dimensions of code and their organization of the world.\'a0Yet to trouble my own polemic, we might also understand the workings of code to have already internalized the visual to the extent that, in the heart of the labs from which UNIX emerged, the cultural processing of the visual via the register of race was already at work in the machine.\cb1 \
\cb3 In extending our critical methodologies,\'a0we must have at least a passing familiarity with code languages, operating systems, algorithmic thinking, and systems design.\'a0We need database literacies, algorithmic literacies, computational literacies, interface literacies.\'a0We need new hybrid\'a0practitioners: artist-theorists, programming humanists, activist-scholars; theoretical archivists, critical race coders.\'a0We need new forms of graduate and undergraduate education that hone both critical and digital literacies.\'a0We have to shake ourselves out of our small, field-based boxes so that we might\'a0take seriously the possibility that our own knowledge practices are normalized, modular, and black boxed\'a0in much the same way as the code we study in our work.\'a0That is,\'a0our very scholarly practices tend to undervalue broad contexts, meaningful relation, and promiscuous border crossing.\'a0While many of us identify as interdisciplinary, very few of us extend that border crossing very far\'a0(theorists tune out the technical; the technologists are impatient of the abstract; scholars of race mock the computational, seeing it as corrupt).\'a0The intense narrowing of our academic specialties over the past fifty years can actually be seen as an effect of or as complicit with the logics of modularity and the relational database.\'a0Just as the relational database works by normalizing data\'97that is, by stripping it of meaningful, idiosyncratic context, creating a system of interchangeable equivalencies\'97our own scholarly practices tend to exist in relatively\'a0hermetically\'a0sealed boxes or nodes.\'a0Critical theory and poststructuralism have been powerful operating systems that have served us well; they were as hard to learn as the complex structures of C++, and we have dutifully learned them.\cb4 \'a0They are also software systems in desperate need of updating and patching. They are lovely, and they are not enough.\cb3 \'a0They cannot be all we do, but that is not to say that they are not of any value.\cb1 \
\cb4 In universities that simply shut down \'93old school\'94 departments\'97like at my university, German and geography; in the UK, Middlesex\'92s philosophy program; in Arizona, perhaps all of ethnic studies; in Albany, anything they can\'97\cb3 scholars must engage the vernacular digital forms that make us nervous,\'a0
\f1\i authoring
\f0\i0 \'a0in them in order to better understand them and to recreate in technological spaces the possibility of doing the work that moves us.\cb4 \'a0\cb3 We need new practices and new modes of collaboration;\'a0we need to be literate in emerging scientific and technological methodologies but also in theories of race, globalization, and gender.\'a0We\'92ll gain that literacy at least\'a0partially through an intellectual generosity or curiosity toward colleagues whose practices are not our own.\'a0We need to privilege systemic modes of thinking that can understand relation and honor complexity, even while valuing precision and specificity.\'a0\cb4 We need\'a0nimbler\'a0ways of\'a0\cb3 linking the network and the node and digital form and content, and we need to understand that categories like race profoundly shape both form\'a0
\f1\i and
\f0\i0 \'a0content\cb4 .\'a0\cb3 In short,\'a0we need a good deal more exchange between the ASA and the digital humanities so that we might develop some shared languages and goals.\'a0We must take seriously the question, why are the digital humanities so white? but also ask why American studies is not more digital.\cb1 \
\cb3 We must remember that\'a0computers are themselves encoders of culture.\'a0If, in the 1960s and 1970s, UNIX hardwired an emerging system of covert racism into our mainframes and our minds,\'a0then computation responds to culture as much as it controls it.\'a0Code and race are deeply intertwined, even as the structures of code labor to disavow these very connections.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0913"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs26\fsmilli13200 \cf5 \cb4 13}}\cb4 \'a0\cb3 Politically committed academics with humanities skill sets must engage technology and its production not simply as an object of our scorn, critique, or fascination but as a productive and generative space that is always emergent and never fully determined.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa96\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 NOTES\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li252\fi-202\sl280\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0901r"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs16\fsmilli8400 \cf5 \cb4 1.}}
\fs16\fsmilli8400 \cb4 \'a0For the past decade, I have had the privilege to work with a team of collaborators on a variety of digital projects, including the online journal\'a0
\f1\i Vectors
\f0\i0 \'a0and a new authoring platform Scalar. In Los Angeles, this team includes Steve Anderson, Craig Dietrich, and Erik Loyer (and, until recently, Raegan Kelly), among others, and it is impossible to overstate how thoroughly I have been reconfigured by the opportunity to interact with such smart and congenial people. Conversations over the years (including at the Baltimore summit) with the broader DH community have deeply shaped our approach to developing computational systems for the humanities.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb4 This essay is a revised version of a piece originally written for\'a0
\f1\i Race after the Internet,
\f0\i0 \'a0edited by Peter Chow-White and Lisa Nakamura, forthcoming from Routledge. Feedback from Neil Fraistat, Matt Gold, David Golumbia, and Steve Ramsay helped sharpen the piece for this volume.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li252\fi-202\sl280\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0902r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb4 2.}}\cb4 \'a0This panel was organized by Glenn Hendler and Bruce Burgett, both of whom have worked quite tirelessly to engage the ASA community in conversations about the digital humanities. In addition to the three of us, Randy Bass, Sharon Daniel, Deborah Kimmey, and Curtis Marez were also on the panel. Tim Powell had been on the original program but was unable to attend.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li252\fi-202\sl280\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0903r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb4 3.}}\cb4 \'a0\cb3 These tensions between traditional humanities scholars and computational humanists are, of course, not new. For examples of these dynamics within early waves of humanities computing, see Thomas, \'93Computing and the Historical Imagination,\'94 and Craig, \'93Stylistic Analysis and Authorship Studies.\'94 As these authors note from within the realms of authorship studies and historical studies, these tensions often played out over the differences between quantitative and qualitative analysis and via debates on the status and validity of various modes of interpretation. Two readers (Golumbia and Ramsay) of this piece during the volume\'92s semiopen peer review process expressed discomfort with the use of the term \'93traditional\'94 to describe humanities scholars who don\'92t consider themselves DHers. I share that discomfort, particularly since the word \'93traditional\'94 seems to imply conservative, not a term many would associate with the ASA today, at least in a political sense. Instead, I mean the term simply to signal scholars in the humanities whose methodologies are not primarily dependent on digital analysis, platforms, or tools.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li252\fi-202\sl280\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0904r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb4 4.}}\cb4 \'a0UNIX develops with some rapidity at least in part because the parent company of Bell Labs, AT&T, was unable to enter the computer business due to a 1958 consent decree. Eric Raymond notes that \'93Bell Labs was required to license its nontelephone technology to anyone who asked\'94 (33). Thus a kind of\'a0\cb3 counterculture chic developed around UNIX\cb4 . Raymond provides a narrative version of this history, including the eventual UNIX wars, in his\'a0
\f1\i The Art of UNIX Programming
\f0\i0 . His account, while thorough,\'a0\cb3 tends to romanticize\cb4 \'a0the collaborative culture around UNIX. For a more objective analysis of the imbrications of the counterculture and early computing cultures, see Fred Turner\'92s\'a0
\f1\i From Counterculture to Cyberculture
\f0\i0 . See also Tom Streeter for a consideration of liberal individualism and computing cultures.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li252\fi-202\sl280\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0905r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb4 5.}}\cb4 \'a0Critical code studies (and software studies more generally) take up the study of computational systems in a variety of ways. For an overview of software studies, see Fuller.\'a0\cb3 For emerging work in critical code studies, see the proceedings of the 2010 conference on Critical Code Studies, archived at\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://vectorsjournal.org/thoughtmesh/critcode"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 http://vectorsjournal.org/thoughtmesh/critcode}}.\cb1 \
