{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0906r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 6.}}\cb4 \'a0Some scholars have questioned the neutral status of digital structures such as code and databases. John Unsworth has situated UNIX as a Western cultural formation, arguing that\'a0\cb3 \'93UNIX is deeply indebted to culturally determined notions such as private property, class membership, and hierarchies of power and effectivity. Most of these ideas are older than the modern Western culture that produced UNIX, but the constellation of cultural elements gathered together in UNIX\'92s basic operating principles seems particularly Western and capitalist\'97not surprisingly, given that its creators were human extensions of one of the largest accumulations of capital in the Western world\'94 (142)\cb4 . See also David Golumbia\'92s observations on the limits of the database and of semantic computing for humanities analysis, as well as work on culturally contextual databases and ontologies undertaken by Kimberly Christen and Ramesh Srinivasan. Golumbia has further argued that object-oriented programming privileges categorization and hierarchies in a manner that has \'93much more to do with engineering presumptions and ideologies than with computational efficiency\'94 (209). His work is\'a0\cb3 a must read for anyone caught up in utopian readings of digital culture\'92s empowering and participatory aspects.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li252\fi-202\sl280\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0907r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb4 7.}}\cb4 \'a0In comments on a draft of this essay, Steve Ramsay suggested that Mike Gancarz\'92s\'a0
\f1\i The Unix Philosophy
\f0\i0 \'a0categorizes UNIX via a related but different rule set. His rule set (4\'965) is as follows:\cb1 \
