{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0909r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb4 9.}}\cb4 \'a0For Gramsci, \'93common sense\'94 is a multilayered phenomenon that can serve both dominant groups and oppressed ones. For oppressed groups, common sense may allow a method of speaking back to power and of rejiggering what counts as sensible. Kara Keeling profitably explores this possibility in her work on the black femme. Computer programmers in the 1970s are interestingly situated. They are on the one hand a subculture (often overlapping with the counterculture), but they are also part of an increasingly managerial class that will help society transition to regimes of neoliberalism and governmentality. Their dreams of libraries of code may be democratic in impulse, but they also increasingly support postindustrial forms of labor.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li252\fi-202\sl280\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/#en0910r"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb4 10.}}\cb4 \'a0Other aspects of UNIX also encode \'93chunking,\'94 including the concept of the file. For a discussion of files in UNIX, see\'a0
\f1\i You Are Not a Gadget
\f0\i0 \'a0by Jaron Lanier. This account of UNIX, among other things, also argues that code and culture exist in complex feedback loops.\cb1 \
